## Now that we have some Data. We should write it into ElasticSearch
This can be done easily using the ElasticSearch spark client.

To make sure your local elasticsearch connection is setup. Try the following. 

1. Open up a bash session inside of the Zeppelin Docker container
~~~
docker exec -it zeppelin bash
~~~

2. Then curl across containers to the `elasticsearch` container over the docker network using the hostname `elasticsearch` instead of localhost
~~~
curl http://elasticsearch:9200/_cat/indices?v
~~~

You should see something like which means you are golden
~~~
health status index                uuid                   pri rep docs.count docs.deleted store.size pri.store.size
green  open   .kibana_task_manager 2APYmb8XRnakzzw93037jQ   1   0          2            0     45.5kb         45.5kb
green  open   .kibana_1            8yBHxJxeQOCCcv3nd90iUQ   1   0          3            0     11.9kb         11.9kb
~~~

## Please go to the Following Link to see what you just wrote

Kibana Index Overview Page: http://localhost:5601/app/kibana#/management/elasticsearch/index_management/indices?_g=()

msg.data:
Please go to the Following Link to see what you just wrote

Kibana Index Overview Page: http://localhost:5601/app/kibana#/management/elasticsearch/index_management/indices?_g=()

We need to actually create an Index Mapping in order for our Timestamps

The following template will declare the mapping property timestamp as type date vs long. This will allow us to create an index.

  1. Open up the Console in ES. http://localhost:5601/app/kibana#/dev_tools/console?_g=()

PUT _template/template_snacks

{  
  "order" : 1,
  "index_patterns" : [
    "snacks*"
  ],
  "settings" : {
    "index" : {
      "lifecycle": {
        "name": "ExpireAfter30Days"
      },
      "number_of_shards" : "1",
      "refresh_interval" : "60s"
    }
  },
  "mappings" : {
    "properties" : {
      "timestamp" : {
        "type": "date"
      }
    }
  },
  "aliases" : { }
}

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Important: Delete the current Index Mapping otherwise the new changes will not take affect
1. Go to the http://localhost:5601/app/kibana#/management/elasticsearch/index_management/indices?_g=()
2. Click on the index `snacks` and `Manage Index` and select `Delete Index`
3. **Note: Don't do this in production environments**. This process should be all controlled by explicit scripts.

## Adding `mapping.id` to each row for Idempotency
~~~
.option("es.mapping.id", "uuid")
~~~

When you declare the `es.mapping.id` it will expect that the DataFrame has that column in it. We will have to add that in order to enable `idempotent` keys.
